    <!-- Philosophy -->
    <section class="mb-12 bg-bg-sanskrit border border-border rounded-lg p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Advaita Vedanta</h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Advaita Vedanta, the non-dualistic school of Vedanta, teaches that Brahman (the absolute reality) 
        and Atman (the individual self) are identical. This fundamental truth - that you are not the limited 
        body-mind complex, but the infinite, eternal consciousness itself - is revealed through the study 
        of the Upanishads under proper guidance.
      </p>
      <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Sri Adi Shankaracharya (788-820 CE) systematized this philosophy through his brilliant commentaries 
        on the Prasthana Trayi and composed numerous prakarana granthas (introductory texts) to make 
        these profound teachings accessible to qualified students.
      </p>
      <div class="bg-bg-white p-4 rounded mt-4">
        <p class="text-text-primary italic text-center">
          "Brahman alone is real, the world is mithya (dependent reality), and the jiva (individual) is none other than Brahman."
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm text-center mt-2">
          - Core teaching of Advaita Vedanta
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

